<h2 id="a-solution">A solution</h2>

<h3 id="a-strategy">A Strategy</h3>
<p class="hint">You do switch. The door you picked only has 1/3 probability of having the prize while the other door has 2/3 probability.</p>

<h3 id="a-description">A Description</h3>
<p class="hint">Letâ€™s pretend like there are two different games: one where you pick one door and no chance to change your mind, and one where you pick two doors and if the car is behind either one you win. Obviously the first has a 1/3 probability and the second has a 2/3 probability of success. You can think of the strategy where you donâ€™t switch as playing the first game and the one where you do switch as playing the second game. In the switching strategy, the first door you pick will never be the one you end with, so really, youâ€™re not picking that door as much as youâ€™re picking the other two and letting the host weed one out. At the end of the day, though, if you play with the switching strategy, then if the prize is behind either of the two doors you picked, you win! So itâ€™s a 2/3 probability if you switch.</p>
